{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"18ee80d6-a01d-450b-a990-b6d45336d9af","content":"Use the `--filter` option:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter FullyQualifiedName~ReportExporterTests\n```\n\nOr filter by class name directly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter ClassName=ReportExporterTests\n```\n\nThe `~` operator means \"contains\", while `=` means exact match. If your class is in a namespace, you may need the fully qualified name with `=`, e.g.:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter FullyQualifiedName~MyNamespace.ReportExporterTests\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c18a40ee-4640-44c8-986a-6fa85e1efd3e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to run only a specific test class using `dotnet test`. This is a straightforward question about the dotnet CLI - I can answer directly without needing to look at the files.\n\nThe standard way to filter by class in `dotnet test` is using the `--filter` option with `FullyQualifiedName` or `ClassName`.","outputTokens":231,"requestId":"BC31:21D6AD:29CA19:30DFEE:69FA9554"},"id":"530e6223-58cf-4c22-b61c-b3374807fe0e","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:11:55.185Z","parentId":"5db0c3cb-ddcd-42ce-9633-3391d020c8d8"}
